Coleus parviflorus

    Authority   Benth.
      Family
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 4768

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A herb with creeping, succulent stems and arimatic
   leaves, producing tubers in clusters at the base of the stems. The
   tubers are round, dark brown or black and aromatic. USES The tubers are
   used in the same way as potatoes. GROWING PERIOD Annual herb, tubers
   may be harvested 120-180 days from planting. COMMON NAMES Sudan potato,
   Madagascar potato, Hausa potato, Koorkan kizhangu, Kentang dwaja,
   Ratala, Country-potato. FURTHER INF Native to tropical Africa, possible
   Ethiopia. Also cultivated in South East Asia. Yields of 3.7-7.5 t/ha of
   tubers have been recorded.

   Sources
   SOURCES (Coleus parviflorus Benth.)
   Tindall H 1983 pp 240 [TEMP, RAIN, USE]
   Duke J 1975 pp 13 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 468 [USE]

